<h2>Ohio Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Ohio homeowners have access to several valuable incentive programs that significantly reduce the cost of solar and HVAC installations. The most substantial benefit is the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which allows homeowners to deduct 30% of the total cost of their solar panel system from their federal taxes. This credit applies to all system components including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation costs, and there is no cap on the credit amount. The 30% rate is available through 2032, after which it will step down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> The 30% federal tax credit applies to the entire cost of solar installation, including equipment and labor. For a \$20,000 system, this represents \$6,000 in tax savings. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds current year tax liability.</li>
<li><strong>Ohio Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Solar energy systems are exempt from property tax assessments in Ohio, meaning the added home value from solar installation won't increase property taxes. This exemption can save homeowners \$200-400 annually depending on local tax rates and system size.</li>
<li><strong>AEP Ohio Energy Efficiency Programs:</strong> AEP Ohio offers rebates up to \$1,200 for high-efficiency HVAC systems, smart thermostats, and other energy efficiency improvements. Heat pump installations can qualify for rebates of \$300-800 depending on efficiency ratings.</li>
<li><strong>FirstEnergy Rebate Programs:</strong> Customers in FirstEnergy territories can receive rebates of \$250-600 for ENERGY STAR certified HVAC equipment, with additional incentives for programmable thermostats and duct sealing services.</li>
<li><strong>Local Utility Programs:</strong> Many Ohio municipal utilities offer additional rebates and financing programs. Columbus offers low-interest loans for energy efficiency improvements, while Cincinnati provides rebates up to \$500 for heat pump installations.</li>
</ul>

